  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why don't install a battery for desktop computer?",
  "response": "There are several reasons why most desktop computers do not have a built-in battery, especially compared to laptops which are designed for portability. Here are some reasons:\n\n1. **Power Source**: Desktops are typically designed to operate while connected to an AC power source. Unlike laptops, they don't need a battery to store energy for portable use since they are usually stationary.\n\n2. **Size and Weight**: Incorporating a battery into a desktop computer could significantly increase its size and weight. This is often undesirable for a device that is meant to remain in one place.\n\n3. **Cost**: Adding a battery would increase the manufacturing and retail costs of desktop computers. Most users prefer to keep prices down for a machine that doesn't need to be portable.\n\n4. **Cooling**: Batteries produce heat, which can complicate the cooling requirements of a desktop. Desktops usually have systems optimized for heat dissipation without the additional warmth generated by a battery.\n\n5. **Power Management**: Desktop computers often feature larger and more powerful power supplies that can handle the demands of high-performance components without the need for a backup battery.\n\n6. **Uninterrupted Power Supply (UPS)**: For users concerned about power interruptions, many opt for a dedicated UPS system that provides battery backup for their desktop without integrating a battery into the computer itself.\n\n7. **Usage Scenarios**: Desktops are typically used in environments where they have continuous power supply (like offices or homes) and aren't subject to the same use cases that make batteries useful in laptops (like commuting or travel).\n\nWhile some all-in-one desktops may include a battery backup feature, traditional desktop towers do not, due to these practical considerations.",
